\begin_layout Abstract
As people are becoming more persistently connected to the Internet, their
 location privacy is becoming an increasing concern.
 The crux of this problem is the link between a mobile device user's identity,
 and the locations that the identity has visited.
 If a mobile device is not linked to a particular identity, then there is
 no location privacy risk.
 I demonstrate the following: (1) a unified model of location profiling,
 privacy, and utility; (2) while GPS provides fine grained location to a
 device and can be turned off, a device's connection to the network inherently
 reveals details about its location; and (3) a practical mobile connectivity
 framework for preserving location privacy is still susceptible to location
 profiling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
First, I present a mathematical model of location profiling based on sequences
 of locations traversed.
 This is a generalization of the above utility and risk model.
 As well, I present a method of simulating a mobility study based on real-world
 data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Subsequently, I present a study where location is inferred from the bandwidth
 changes a phone incurs while travelling along a path.
 The attacker in this case is anyone who is able to send a constant stream
 of data to the phone.
 This study demonstrated that with 70% accuracy, a classifer could determine
 on which path among 8 a cell phone is travelling.
 Second, I look at the ability to use location profiling to identify a user.
 I explore the possibility that an attacker could place geo-locating code
 in a mobile ad and use the information gathered to uniquely identify a
 user whose location habits are known.
 I also demonstrate that ads are an effective method of conducting mobility
 studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Finally, I look at the possibility of the cell service provider determining
 a user's location.
 This is trivial in a typical cell network, using cell tower triangulation.
 Using our framework, a privacy-enthusiastic provider could provide service
 and accept payment without knowing a user's identity.
 However, even in such a case, location profiling is possible.
 We present a model of utility and risk where a user can determine based
 on their own knowledge of location profiling how likely they would be identifie
d among other users.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
With the modern ubiquity of mobile devices, the ability of a user to be
 located at most times of the day in their lives is a new force to contend
 with.
 With the convenience of staying connected constantly, there is a risk of
 being located or identified.
 We would like to be able to quantify that risk, as well as allow this informati
on to be transparent to the user, so that they can make informed decisions
 about whether to remain connected.
\end_layout

