\begin_layout Chapter*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Users didn't used to care about location privacy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bah"

\end_inset

.
 However, revelations from the 2013 global surveillance disclosures
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Snowden
\end_layout

\end_inset

 have caused many to become more concerned about their privacy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bah"

\end_inset

.
 These concerns have had a chilling effect on users' usage of digital devices
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bah"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The state of users' location privacy is nebulous.
 A poor understanding of what is possible has made it difficult for a user
 to quantify the value of privacy.
 Moreover, access to privacy enhancing tools is limited to those who have
 technical proficiency and have put in the effort to learn about their options
 or evade surveillance.
 While a user may be disturbed by how much access some companies or governments
 have to their location information, their inability to quantify its value
 and the high barrier to access privacy enhancing technologies prevent them
 from taking steps to mitigate their concerns.
 In many cases, users irrationally choose immediate gratification at the
 cost of future consequences in terms of privacy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aim of this thesis is twofold.
 The first goal is to bring to light the practical ability of different
 actors --- government, service provider, or service --- to potentially
 infringe on a user's location privacy.
 By quantifying the bounds of location privacy, we may gain a clearer understand
ing of which behaviours are risky, and which are safe, in terms of protecting
 their location information.
 The second goal is to develop privacy enhancing technologies which may
 make location privacy easier for an individual to guard against the abovementio
ned actors; to make privacy more accessible to everyday users.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most research in this field has been conducted within the context of location
 based services (LBS) --- things like online map queries, geotagging services.
 I expand this scope of study and focus on the location privacy issues in
 non-LBS contexts by developing a model of utility versus location privacy.
 I then explore several scenarios where non-LBS use of a mobile device may
 reveal location.
 Finally, I discuss frameworks that could be used to allow for greater location
 privacy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Contributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I begin by defining the scope of this problem in terms of potential adversaries,
 vectors of attack, and user behaviours.
 I develop a model of user behaviour, privacy, and utility.
 Using this model, I evaluate threats to privacy in the context of different
 attackers: a streaming service, an ad vendor, and a mobile service provider;
 I also explore the effects of limiting usage of these services or applications
 as a way to increase privacy.
 Finally, I will explore in detail a privacy-preserving anonymous mobile
 framework and its ability to increase location privacy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
1.
 Model and quantify non-LBS usage and location privacy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been many attempts to quantify location privacy in terms of location
 based services.
 However, none that I know of have accounted for the fact that simply by
 being online or using a service, an anonymous user may be identified by
 location profiling if an attacker controls her means of connection.
 In Chapter 1, I present a risk-utility model that can be used to measure
 the threat of non-LBS usage to location privacy.
 The utility model allows for a more flexible and valid estimation of what
 a user may desire.
 I demonstrate the ability to use location profiling to identify a subject
 using this model, and the different strategies a user could attempt to
 foil basic location profiling.
 I also conduct a field survey to evaluate the privacy-utility balance in
 practice.
 This model, and results from the survey, provide a basis for the remainder
 of my dissertation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
2.
 Measure the potential for a webservice to attack location privacy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While a user or service may have the ability to protect explicit location
 information to some degree, an web service may still illegitimately infer
 a user's location from metadata.
 In Chapter 2, I present a method in which a music streaming service may
 determine the location of a user by analyzing the wavering connection quality.
 I show that by using sequence matching algorithms, a remote web service
 may reveal the geographic path of a user given several choices, with no
 upstream information from the user except TCP ACKs.
 I also explore the traffic shaping a user could employ to prevent this
 risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
3.
 Measure the potential for an ad vendor to compromise location privacy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While a user may give a certain LBS permission to use location information,
 that service may unknown to the user forward that information to an ad
 service.
 In Chapter 3, I explore the ability for an ad service to deanonymize a
 user using her location information.
 Ads are bought, and location data is analyzed to see how many users offer
 location information over a longer period of time.
 I then analyze the risk presented by certain types of apps, as well as
 whether limiting the usage of a certain essential LBS can reduce the risk
 of even targetted deanonymization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
4.
 Develop a framework for a mobile vendor to implement a privacy-oriented
 mobile network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With users' trust in mobile network operators eroding, they may seek a privacy-o
riented alternative that does not require them to reveal their location.
 The solution is a mobile network that breaks the link between mobile identifier
 and actual user.
 In Chapter 4, I present a protocol that allows users to conveniently obtain
 a temporary mobile identifier, which can be changed as soon as location
 profiling becomes a risk.
 I evaluate the ability for users to minimize their risk of having their
 identity revealed when using an anonymous service such as this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
5.
 Present and evaluate a framework for convenient anonymous cell phone usage
 with trusted peers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative to using a privacy-oriented framework is sharing credentials
 with a trusted user in order to create a mix-zone of identifiers.
 A user is typically authenticated on a mobile network through an attach
 procedure that results in a temporary authentication key.
 By sharing this key, a user may provide some privacy protection to another
 user, while at the same time increasing their own privacy.
 In Chapter 5, I present a protocol to allow sharing of these keys.
 I analyze sharing behaviour in terms of risk and utility.
 I implement and evaluate this protocol in the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Collaborators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All research acitvities are conducted under the supervision of Brian Levine.
 Preliminary work for Chapter 2 was completed in collaboration with Hamed
 Soroush, Erik Learned-Miller, Marc Liberatore, Joydeep Biswas, and Brian
 Levine.
 Preliminary work for Chapters 4 and 5 was completed in collaboration with
 Marc Liberatore, Mariya Zheleva, and Brian Levine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Model of location privacy and utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Current models of location privacy primarily model threats from location
 based services, and propose defenses based on differential privacy strategies
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bah"

\end_inset

.
 However, these studies do not consider the threats from privacy introduced
 by simply using a service.
 In this chapter, I generalize an existing method of quantifying location
 privacy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shokri2011quantifying"

\end_inset

, and extend it to allow for threats from non-LBS service usage.
 In my preliminary work, I look at potential vectors for attacking location
 privacy, and argue for an economic model of privacy.
 I propose to adapt a game theoretic model of location privacy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "freudiger2009non"

\end_inset

, and an information theoretic model of privacy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sankar2013utility"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Preliminary work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I employ a utility model to quantify location privacy.
 I define the scope of this model by summarizing the different adversaries
 and types of threats against location privacy.
 Next, I formalize the framework behind several of these problems.
 I then discuss several possible scenarios and how they fit in this framework.
 Finally, I evaluate the risk-privacy balance with respect to a mobility
 dataset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Overview
\end_layout

