\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Potential vulnerabilities in location privacy.
 User, mobile device, and base station are in some physical location.
 Solid colored lines indicate information known to a potential attacker.
 Dotted colored lines indicate information that may be inferred by an attacker.
 Red lines indicate information known to a service provider; blue an advertising
 client, green a web service.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Potential-vulnerabilities-in"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many ways people remain connected to the Internet --- Wi-Fi, cellular
 network, cable.
 In each of these cases, the time and location of a user connection is known
 to the service provider.
 There have been cases of IMSI-catchers being used dubiously to monitor
 individuals.
 Additionally, passive eavesdropping techniques may intercept any mode of
 wireless signal, including Bluetooth, allow for a varying degree of granularity
 to localize an individual.
 We need a flexible framework to model these types of attacks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many vectors of attack on a user's location privacy.
 Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Potential-vulnerabilities-in"

\end_inset

 diagrams the potential vulnerabilities from different classes of attackers.
 In Chapters 2 and 3, I look at two types of remote attackers: ad vendors
 and web services.
 In Chapters 4 and 5, I look at service provider attackers, and how to defend
 against them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Utility-privacy framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previous work has used k-anonymity, or (k, p)-anonymity as a privacy metric.
 We use the economic measure of utility as a metric for two reasons: (1)
 it allows us to balance the cost of utility with the cost of privacy loss,
 and (2) it allows us to assign different values to different locations.
 For example, a user could have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

significant stays
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at home and work, a place where they would likely be identified, anyway,
 so achieving location privacy here is not worth it if they are able to
 change identities without being easily linked once they leave work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our model, there are users, U and attackers, A.
 Each user travels to locations S of varying granularity, and connects at
 certain times, and sends certain data to untrusted peers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be the user and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be the attacker.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 seeks to maximize utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{U}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 seeks to maximize utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several factors affect these utility values, and their weights are tunable.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{U}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
