\begin_layout Chapter
Location privacy threats from a streaming service
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter explores the threats to location privacy when a user downloads
 data while in motion, and an evaluation on the loss of utility if a user
 attempts to reduce these threats.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This chapter is based on work published at the 
\shape italic
Privacy Enhancing Technologies Symposium
\shape default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "soroush2013turning"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Preliminary work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite features on smartphones to ensure location privacy, a user’s whereabouts
 can be remotely deduced.
 A remote party communicating with a phone has a window into the complex
 interactions between phone and cell tower.
 These features can be used to reveal the phone’s location, or at least
 significantly narrow the list of possible paths taken by a phone and its
 owner.
 This information is leaked regardless of application-level privacy settings.
 Cell phone users have such experiences intuitively in many common situations.
 For example, a caller may be able to tell when a friend has entered an
 elevator based solely on call quality; or a user may notice a loss in data
 throughput during a subway ride.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(copy a bunch of stuff from paper)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Proposed work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Investigate the use of a hidden semi-Markov model as a sequence matching
 algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Additional measurements to determine the effect of time of day and other
 factors
\end_layout

