\begin_layout Chapter
Location privacy threats from an ad service
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Location based services that contain mobile advertisements forward this
 information on to ad vendors and their clients.
 These include popular mobile apps such as Grindr, The Weather Channel,
 and Words With Friends.
 An advertising client can purchase advertising through an affiliate, and
 some affiliates allow for the client to inject JavaScript in the ad.
 As soon as the ad is displayed on one of these ads, the script runs and
 in some cases sends data to the ad client along with a randomly chosen
 advertising ID that is unique to the device.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These ads ostensibly allow advertisers to target certain users depending
 on information such as location.
 Location information alone can allow advertisers to see where an app is
 used the most, and target future advertising to those locations.
 However, simply anonymizing location data does not protect a user from
 location profiling.
 Deanonymizing some of these users may be trivial, if, for example, the
 user uses the app at work or at home the majority of the time.
 While users may trust the application they are using with location information,
 they likely do not trust advertising clients.
 As well, this information is rarely protected by any sort of privacy policy[i
 think].
 Most alarmingly, anybody can be an advertiser, and target any geographic
 location, for a very low cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Malicious intent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several ways location data obtained from advertising can be used
 maliciously.
 It would be very cost effective for an attacker to determine where, for
 example, gay users are located, by targeting advertising in a certain city
 and looking at the coordinates located in residential areas of users who
 used Grindr.
 As well, attackers could deanonymize a particular user and target that
 user to see in realtime their location or predict their location based
 on history; this would allow them to stalk the user or determine if the
 user is home.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stalking is a particularly real danger posed by advertising.
 If a stalker knows where a victim spends a lot of their time, and the victim
 happens to be using one of the popular apps that are part of the advertising
 network that the stalker is on, they can be followed.
 We explore this danger further by looking at how many users are trackable
 this easily.
 We postulate that there are broadly three kinds of users: those who use
 apps at home for the most part, those who use them in a handful of places,
 and those who use them in many places.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We explore also the concept of mix zones, and how they may both be beneficial
 and harmful to a person's privacy.
 On the one hand, a user may want to choose a more populated area to use
 an app without being deanonymized.
 On the other hand, if a person is part of an entourage that does not wish
 to be stalked, a single person in that entourage could compromise the entire
 group's privacy by using a privacy-leaking app.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Preliminary work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Experimental design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To quantify the threat of stalking using an ad service, I plan to verify
 the following hypotheses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Users can be seen multiple times, at low cost.
 We can manipulate how many times each user sees an ad through the bidding
 settings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There are significant amounts of users in each category of: homebodies,
 schleps, nomads.
 Homebodies and schleps are defined as users with 1 or 2 significant stay
 locations.
 Nomads have no geographic signature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It should be fairly easy to identify a homebody or schlep based on significant
 stays.
 There are possible scenarios: 1.
 Consider a person whose details we know about (home, work), and we wish
 to identify.
 In our experiments, the identified significant stays serve as a surrogate
 for the outside information we'd have for the person.
 2.
 Consider a homebody who has an ad-id initially, and then turns off her
 ad-id.
 Can we deanonymize a query from that location
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given a list of locations, we can identify nomads by targeting ad-ids in
 certain locations.
 We set ads to be shown only once per user each day, and correlate IDs with
 locations travelled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Nomads with anonymous ids may be deanonymized by cotravellers with deanonymized
 ids.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Preliminary experiments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The existing dataset contains 350k impressions from 141k users.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I validate the first three hypotheses using this dataset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first do a survey of types of users in our dataset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 100 users who are in the dataset 40 or more times.
 (40 impressions)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For users that have seen ads 10 or more times, deanonymization based on
 location is accurate 39% of the time, testing and training before and after
 the median times of access.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of the 3% of users who had 10 or more impressions, 50% are seen at the same
 one location for at least 3 times a week, 10% at two locations, 1% at 3
 locations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
50% have no geographic signature.
\end_layout

